# I Solved 50+ PortSwigger Labs. Here's What They Didn't Teach Me.

When I first started learning web security, I thought solving PortSwigger labs would automatically make me good at bug bounty hunting.

After all, I was learning IDORs, authentication flaws, access control issues, CSRF, SQL injection, and much more.

So I completed lab after lab.

Then I opened my first real bug bounty target.

And suddenly...

I felt like a beginner again.

## Labs Give You Confidence

Real Applications Test It.

PortSwigger is one of the best learning platforms I've ever used.

It teaches you how vulnerabilities work.

It teaches you how to exploit them safely.

It teaches you the theory behind modern web security.

But real applications don't come with a label saying:

*"This page contains an IDOR."*

That's where things become different.

## The Biggest Difference

In PortSwigger, you already know there's a vulnerability.

Your job is simply to find the right path.

In bug bounty...

You don't even know if a vulnerability exists.

That completely changes your mindset.

Instead of exploiting known bugs, you're trying to understand an application built by hundreds of developers over many years.

Sometimes you spend three hours testing a feature...

Only to realize it's implemented correctly.

That isn't failure.

That's part of the process.

## I Had to Stop Chasing Endpoints

Earlier, I used to jump from page to page looking for something interesting.

Now I spend more time understanding the application itself.

Questions like these help me more than any scanner:

- What is this feature supposed to do?
- Who owns this data?
- Should another user ever see this?
- Where does the server trust user input?
- What assumptions did the developer make?

Those questions have improved my testing far more than learning another Burp extension.

## One Lesson I'll Never Forget

A lab teaches you one vulnerability.

A real application teaches you how systems are built.

That's why even when I don't find a valid bug, I still learn something.

Maybe I understand GraphQL a little better.

Maybe I learn how a wishlist feature works.

Maybe I discover a new API pattern.

Every application leaves me with something useful.

## My Advice for Beginners

Don't rush through PortSwigger just to complete all the labs.

After every lab, ask yourself:

"Where would this vulnerability appear in a real application?"

That one question completely changes how you learn.

Because your goal isn't to collect lab badges.

Your goal is to recognize similar patterns when no one tells you where to look.

## What's Next for Me

I'm still learning.

Still testing.

Still submitting reports.

Some will be Informative.

Some may be duplicates.

Hopefully, some will become valid findings.

But one thing has changed.

I'm no longer treating PortSwigger as the finish line.

I'm treating it as the training ground.

And honestly...

That's when learning became much more enjoyable.

